        <p><strong>Speed winner: Banana Gun</strong> ” Its proprietary node infrastructure gives it a clear edge in raw execution speed. Banana Gun is consistently 100-200ms faster than its closest competitor (Trojan), which in the world of new token launches can be the difference between getting in at the bottom of the initial pump curve or buying the top.</p>



        <p>However, it's important to note that <strong>speed differences matter most for sniping new launches</strong>. For standard swaps on existing tokens with established liquidity, the gap between all four bots narrows significantly ” we're talking about whether your swap executes in 0.3 seconds vs 0.5 seconds, which is negligible for most trading strategies.</p>



        <!-- ============================================ -->

        <h2>5. MEV Protection and Anti-Sandwich Features</h2>



        <p>MEV (Maximal Extractable Value) attacks ” specifically sandwich attacks ” are the silent portfolio killer for meme coin traders. A sandwich attack occurs when a malicious validator or bot sees your pending transaction, front-runs it (buying before you), and then back-runs it (selling after you), pocketing the difference. On low-liquidity meme coins, sandwich attacks can cost you 5-20% per trade.</p>



        <table>

            <thead>

                <tr>

                    <th>Feature</th>

                    <th>Trojan</th>

                    <th>BonkBot</th>

                    <th>Maestro</th>

                    <th>Banana Gun</th>

                </tr>

            </thead>

            <tbody>

                <tr>

                    <td>Private Mempool Routing</td>

                    <td>�… Yes</td>

                    <td>�… Yes</td>

                    <td>�… Yes</td>

                    <td>�… Yes</td>

                </tr>

                <tr>

                    <td>Anti-Sandwich Mode</td>

                    <td>�… Advanced (configurable)</td>

                    <td>�… Standard</td>

                    <td>�… Standard</td>

                    <td>�… Advanced (auto-detect)</td>

                </tr>

                <tr>

                    <td>Slippage Protection</td>

                    <td>�… Auto + Manual, per-token whitelist</td>

                    <td>�… Smart Slippage (auto)</td>

                    <td>�… Manual (% or absolute)</td>

                    <td>�… Auto + Manual</td>

                </tr>

                <tr>

                    <td>MEV Refund Program</td>

                    <td>�… Yes (partial refund on detected attacks)</td>

                    <td>�Œ No</td>

                    <td>�Œ No</td>

                    <td>�Œ No</td>

                </tr>

                <tr>

                    <td>Transaction Simulation</td>

                    <td>�… Before submit</td>

                    <td>�… Before submit</td>

                    <td>�… Before submit</td>

                    <td>�… Before submit</td>

                </tr>

                <tr>

                    <td>Jito Bundle Support</td>

                    <td>�… Yes</td>

                    <td>�… Yes</td>

                    <td>�… Yes</td>

                    <td>�… Yes</td>

                </tr>

            </tbody>

        </table>



        <p><strong>MEV winner: Trojan</strong> ” Trojan's configurable anti-sandwich mode, combined with its MEV refund program and per-token slippage whitelist, makes it the most sophisticated MEV protection suite available. The MEV refund program is unique: if a sandwich attack is detected on one of your trades, Trojan automatically refunds a percentage of the extracted value from its treasury.</p>



        <div class="warning-box">

            <strong>�� MEV Reality Check</strong>

            <p>No bot can 100% prevent sandwich attacks. Private mempool routing and Jito bundles significantly reduce the risk, but determined validators with specialized infrastructure can still extract MEV from low-slippage, high-priority-fee trades. The safest strategy: use private mempool routing, set reasonable slippage (8-15% for meme coins, never higher than 25%), and avoid trading tokens with less than $50K in liquidity when the chain is congested.</p>

        </div>



        <!-- ============================================ -->

        <h2>6. User Experience and Interface Comparison</h2>



        <p>All four bots operate through Telegram, but their interfaces and command structures differ significantly. Here's how they compare on UX:</p>



        <h3>Trojan ” Power User's Dream</h3>

        <p>Trojan's interface is dense but powerful. It offers an inline command system (<code>/buy [token] [amount] [slippage] [priority]</code>) that lets experienced traders execute complex trades in a single message. The settings menu is comprehensive but can be overwhelming for beginners ” expect to spend 20-30 minutes configuring your default parameters before your first trade. Once configured, however, trading is lightning-fast.</p>



        <h3>BonkBot ” Beginner-Friendly Simplicity</h3>

        <p>BonkBot has the cleanest UX of the four. Commands are intuitive (<code>/buy [token] [SOL amount]</code>), and most settings have sensible defaults that work well for casual traders. The "Smart Slippage" feature means you rarely need to think about slippage at all. For traders who want to open Telegram, type one command, and get a fill, BonkBot is the smoothest experience.</p>



        <h3>Maestro ” Feature Overload</h3>

        <p>Maestro has the most commands, sub-menus, and configuration options of any bot. This is both its greatest strength and biggest weakness. Experienced traders who want granular control over every aspect of their trades will love it. Beginners will feel lost. Maestro's /help menu returns pages of commands ” expect a learning curve of several days.</p>



        <h3>Banana Gun ” Speed-First Minimalism</h3>

        <p>Banana Gun's interface is intentionally minimal ” a stripped-down command set optimized for speed. Commands are short (single letters for common actions), and the bot prioritizes getting your transaction submitted over fancy visual feedback. The trade-off: less customization, fewer order types, and no copy trading.</p>



        <div class="pro-tip">

            <strong>�™� UX Recommendation by Experience Level</strong>

            <p><strong>Beginners:</strong> Start with BonkBot. Its simple interface and smart defaults will get you trading in under 5 minutes. <strong>Intermediate:</strong> Trojan offers the best balance of features and usability. <strong>Advanced:</strong> Maestro gives you the deepest control, especially for copy trading and multi-chain strategies.</p>

        </div>



        <!-- ============================================ -->

        <h2>7. Security Track Record: Who Has Been Breached?</h2>



        <p>Security is the most overlooked aspect of Telegram bot selection. These bots require token approval for your wallet ” meaning if the bot's backend is compromised, your funds are at risk. Here's the security history of each bot:</p>



        <table>

            <thead>

                <tr>

                    <th>Bot</th>

                    <th>Security Incidents</th>

                    <th>Wallet Model</th>

